# Orchestrate GitHub issues pipeline (Stage 5)

**Inputs**:
- The GitHub repo (currently `qualabs/sgai-for-mpeg-dash`) at run time
  via `gh issue list/view`. The orchestrator does not read a local
  cache of issues — it always queries GitHub fresh.
- `.env.agent` at the project root. Required keys:
  - `TRUSTED_GH_USERS` — comma-separated GitHub logins that allow the
    full auto cycle (D2).
  - Optional `NOTEBOOK_ID` — passed through to `analyze-impact`
    when a Flow B issue trips the keyword detector.
- The repo working tree (`context/`, `context-analysis/`, `output/`,
  `output-analysis/`) — used by `propose-response` for grounding.
- Invocation flags (parsed from the command line):
  - `--dry-run` (default) — produce all artefacts under
    `.github-ai/output-issues/<issue-N>/` but do NOT call `gh issue
    comment` and do NOT apply any labels on GitHub.
  - `--live` — same as `--dry-run` PLUS post the drafted response
    and apply labels via `gh` (see `post-response.prompt`).
  - `--issue <N>` (optional, repeatable) — restrict the run to one or
    more explicit issue numbers (useful for re-runs / smoke tests).
    When absent, the orchestrator processes every issue surfaced by
    `detect-issues`.

**Output**:
- One `.github-ai/output-issues/<issue-N>/` subfolder per processed
  issue, containing:
  - `meta.md` — **regenerated every run** with a fresh snapshot of
    the issue (title, body verbatim, labels, comments timeline). No
    history; the file mirrors the issue's current state.
  - `cycle-<C>/triage.md` — always written for the current cycle.
  - `cycle-<C>/impact.md` — only for Flow B issues.
  - `cycle-<C>/response.md` — the drafted reply for the current
    cycle.
  Where `<C>` is the cycle index (`1` on first run, `2` after the
  OP has replied to a prior AI response, etc.) computed by
  `detect-issues.prompt`. Each cycle's artefacts live in their own
  subfolder, preserving the audit trail across re-runs.
- A single end-of-run **summary block on stdout** (delimited by
  `=== SGAI-ISSUES RUN SUMMARY ===` / `=== END SUMMARY ===`) listing
  counts, per-issue verdicts, cycle indices, labels applied, and the
  outsider attention list. The parent agent picks this block up and
  relays it to Nicolas on Telegram — the orchestrator itself never
  sends Telegram messages.

**Skip if**: never. The orchestrator is always invoked manually
(D7); it decides per-issue whether work is needed by reading the
issue's label set (see Step 1).

**Execution mode**: foreground, single subagent. NO nested
subagents (the parent agent that invokes this prompt is the only
delegation boundary). The orchestrator itself reads the per-step
prompts inline and applies them — there is no `claude -p` recursion.

**Default policy**: dry-run (D1). The orchestrator never posts to
GitHub unless `--live` is explicitly passed.

---

## Setup

1. Parse the invocation flags. If neither `--dry-run` nor `--live`
   appears, assume `--dry-run`. If both appear, abort with an error
   to stdout — the operator must pick one.
2. Source `.env.agent` at the project root. Parse
   `TRUSTED_GH_USERS` into a set. If the file is missing or the
   variable is empty, log a warning and treat the trusted set as
   empty (every author will be treated as an outsider).
3. Resolve the GitHub repo from `git remote get-url origin`
   (normalise to `<owner>/<repo>`). Log it as
   `[REPO=<owner>/<repo>]`.
4. Log a single mode line:
   `[MODE=<dry-run|live>] [TRUSTED=<comma-list>]`.

## Pipeline

For each step below, log:
`[STAGE-5 <step> issue=<N>] <one-line status>`.

### Step 1 — Detect issues to process

Apply the body of `.github-ai/prompts/issues/detect-issues.prompt`.
Result: an array of `{number, title, body, author, created_at,
labels, raw_lang_hint, cycle_count}` records, filtered to **open**
issues whose label set contains NONE of:

- `ai-triaged`
- `ai-responded`
- `ai-skipped`
- `ai-needs-review`
- `ai-conversation-cap-hit`

`detect-issues` ALSO drops issues that have reached the anti-loop
cap (D5 — `cycle_count >= 4`): it applies the
`ai-conversation-cap-hit` label in `--live` mode and excludes the
issue from the returned set. The orchestrator never sees those
issues in the loop below.

If the invocation passed `--issue <N>` one or more times, restrict
the result to those numbers regardless of label state (the operator
is explicitly re-targeting). The cap (D5) still applies on a
forced re-run — `detect-issues` will refuse to return an issue at
`cycle_count >= 4` even when explicitly listed.

Log: `[STAGE-5 detect] <count> issue(s) to process: [<N1>@cycle<C1>, <N2>@cycle<C2>, ...]`.
If `count == 0`, jump straight to the summary block.

### Step 2 — Per-issue loop

For each issue record from Step 1, in numerical order. Let `C =
issue.cycle_count` (computed by `detect-issues`; always `>= 1` and
`<= 3` for any issue that survived Step 1).

#### 2.0 — Regenerate `meta.md`

BEFORE invoking any of the per-step prompts, regenerate the issue's
`meta.md` snapshot so the cycle subfolders sit alongside an
up-to-date context anchor. Fetch the issue with comments:

```bash
gh issue view <N> \
  --repo <owner>/<repo> \
  --json number,title,body,author,createdAt,updatedAt,state,labels,comments
```

Write `.github-ai/output-issues/issue-<N>/meta.md` (create the parent
folder if absent) using this exact shape:

````markdown
# Issue #<N> — <title>

- **Number**: #<N>
- **URL**: https://github.com/<owner>/<repo>/issues/<N>
- **Author**: <login> (https://github.com/<login>)
- **Author trust**: trusted | outsider
- **Created**: <ISO timestamp>
- **Updated**: <ISO timestamp>
- **State**: open | closed
- **Labels (current)**: <comma-separated list, or "(none)">

## Original body (verbatim)

> <body line by line, blockquoted — preserve markdown / fenced
> blocks as-is inside the blockquote prefix>

## Comments timeline

| # | Author | Date | Snippet (first 80 chars) |
|---|--------|------|--------------------------|
| 1 | <login> | <ISO> | "<first 80 chars of body>…" |
| ... | ... | ... | ... |

(If there are no comments, write "(no comments yet)" instead of
the table.)

Last refreshed: <orchestrator run timestamp, ISO-8601>
````

`meta.md` is **always overwritten** on every run — there is no
history. It is the up-to-date snapshot the cycle subfolders point
back to. Author trust is resolved as `trusted` if `login ∈
TRUSTED_GH_USERS`, else `outsider`.

Log: `[STAGE-5 meta issue=<N>] regenerated meta.md (cycle=<C>)`.

#### 2.1 — Triage

Apply `.github-ai/prompts/issues/triage-issue.prompt` against the
issue, passing `cycle_count = C` as an input. Write the verdict to
`.github-ai/output-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C>/triage.md` (create the
cycle subfolder if absent). Capture the structured fields:
- `flow`: `A` | `B` | `C` | `SKIP`
- `severity`: `cosmetic` | `spec-detail` | `requirements` |
  `architectural`
- `lang`: ISO-639-1 (`en`, `es`, `pt`, `fr`, `it`, `de`, …) with
  `en` as fallback if detection is inconclusive (D4)
- `trusted`: boolean (`author ∈ TRUSTED_GH_USERS`?)
- `cycle_count`: echo of `C` from `detect-issues` (no recomputation
  inside the triage prompt — `detect-issues` is the single source
  of truth for the cycle index, and applies the anti-loop cap D5
  before this step is reached).

If `flow == SKIP`, the issue does not get a response. In `--live`
mode, apply the `ai-skipped` label and stop processing this issue.
Continue with the next.

#### 2.2 — Impact analysis (Flow B only)

If `flow == B`, apply `.github-ai/prompts/issues/analyze-impact.prompt`
against the issue. The keyword detector runs inside that prompt
(D6); the orchestrator does not pre-filter. Write the result to
`.github-ai/output-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C>/impact.md`.

For `flow ∈ {A, C}` skip this step.

#### 2.3 — Propose response

Apply `.github-ai/prompts/issues/propose-response.prompt`, passing
`cycle_count = C` so the draft can adapt its tone for follow-up
cycles (`C > 1` ⇒ acknowledge the prior AI response and address
the OP's new feedback). The prompt also adapts the draft shape to
the flow (A / B / C) and injects the auto-draft disclaimer at the
top if `severity ∈ {requirements, architectural}` (D3). Write the
draft to `.github-ai/output-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C>/response.md`.

#### 2.4 — Post or hold

Decide whether to post:

- If `trusted == true` AND `--live` is set → apply
  `.github-ai/prompts/issues/post-response.prompt`. It reads the
  current cycle's draft at
  `.github-ai/output-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C>/response.md`, posts
  the comment via `gh issue comment`, and applies the labels
  `ai-responded`, `severity:<severity>`, `flow:<flow>`. On
  success, mark this issue as `posted`.
- If `trusted == false` (outsider) → do NOT post regardless of
  mode. In `--live` mode, apply the `ai-needs-review` label so
  Nicolas can see at a glance which issues are waiting on his
  approval (D2). The response draft is still saved under
  `.github-ai/output-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C>/response.md`. Mark the
  issue as `needs-review`.
- If `--dry-run` → do not post and do not apply labels; mark the
  issue as `dry-drafted`.

### Step 3 — Summary block

After the loop, emit to stdout:

```
=== SGAI-ISSUES RUN SUMMARY ===
mode: <dry-run|live>
repo: <owner>/<repo>
processed: <count>
  - <N>: cycle=<C> flow=<F> severity=<S> lang=<L> trusted=<bool> state=<posted|needs-review|dry-drafted|skipped>
  - ...
cap-hit (D5 anti-loop, dropped before triage):
  - <N>: <title> by <author> (cycle_count=<C>)
  - ...
needs-review (outsiders awaiting Nicolas decision):
  - <N>: cycle=<C> <title> by <author>
  - ...
labels applied (live mode only):
  - <N>: [ai-responded, severity:<S>, flow:<F>]
  - ...
=== END SUMMARY ===
```

If counts are zero in any subsection, emit `(none)` rather than
omitting the heading — the parent agent's regex relies on the
section being present.

## Notes for future cron integration (D7)

Manual invocation today. When the trigger flips to cron:

- The cron job should pass `--dry-run` first, save the summary block
  to a fresh log, and only escalate to `--live` if the operator
  reviewed the dry run.
- Or skip the dry-run gating and run `--live` directly — but only
  after `TRUSTED_GH_USERS` is wide enough that the
  `ai-needs-review` queue stays manageable.
- Either way, the cron driver writes the summary block to a file
  that the Telegram-notify hook tails — same parent-agent contract
  as today.
